+---
+title: Execution patterns
+description: How queue-level execution patterns (static-dag, pipeline, map-reduce) layer above the engine tick, how the gate/respawn lineage works, the extendRun + run.extended audit seam, and the forward-arc-never-rewind invariant that keeps every run graph acyclic.
+---
+
+The core orchestrator engine ā€” ticks, `depends_on` resolution, resource locks,
+fire-and-reconcile ā€” knows nothing about *what shape* a run should have. It
+schedules items; it does not decide whether more items should exist. **Execution
+patterns** fill that gap. A pattern is a per-queue strategy object that sits
+*above* the engine: after each engine tick the orchestrator runs a **pattern
+phase** that may decide to extend the run with new items, and those items flow
+right back into the unchanged engine on the next tick.
+
+This page explains the three built-in patterns, how you configure them on a
+queue, the `extendRun` seam and its audit trail, and the invariant that keeps
+every dynamically grown run graph correct.
+
+For the engine tick mechanics that patterns build on, see
+[How an offload run executes](/agora/explanation/how-offload-runs/). For the run
+graph format that `extendRun` validates against, see the
+[plan.json reference](/agora/reference/plan-json/).
+
+## The three patterns
+
+Each pattern is a strategy object with two pure hooks. `plan(run)` expands or
+normalizes a submission before validation runs at submit time. `onTaskDone(item,
+ctx)` fires once per terminal item of an in-scope run on every tick and either
+returns a `SpawnDirective` (new items + edges) or `null`. Patterns keep no
+state of their own; `ctx.runItems` (the de-namespaced view of the whole run) is
+the pattern's entire world.
+
+### `static-dag`
+
+The default. Its `plan` is the identity, and `onTaskDone` always returns
+`null` ā€” the run's item set is fixed at submit time and the engine works
+through it to completion. Use this whenever you know the full work graph up
+front. It is the simplest and most predictable shape: audit trail, provenance
+closure, and retry semantics are fully determined before a single item fires.
+
+### `pipeline`
+
+A pipeline run is a sequence of items that have already been declared on the
+run at submit time. The pattern does two things:
+
+- **`plan` auto-chains the items.** Every item past the first whose
+  `depends_on` is empty gets `depends_on: [previousItem.id]` injected. You
+  submit the items in order; the pattern makes each one wait for the one
+  before it. There is no `stages` schema and no fan-out ā€” just a linear
+  chain expressed through ordinary `depends_on` edges.
+- **`onTaskDone` spawns a fix lineage when a gate goes red.** A gate item
+  is any item whose reserved `inputs.gate` key carries a `GateConfig`:
+
+  ```ts
+  interface GateConfig {
+    onRed: 'advance' | 'spawn-fix';
+    subject: string;              // itemId whose product is being gated
+    fixTemplate?: SpawnTemplate;
+    maxFixAttempts?: number;      // default 1
+  }
+  ```
+
+  When a `spawn-fix` gate finishes red, the pattern asks `respawnLineage`
+  for the new items to append.
+
+On a clean pass the pattern is a no-op: the engine's normal dep-resolver
+advances to the next pre-declared item because its `depends_on` already
+points at the just-completed item. Forward progress is the engine's
+ordinary work; the pattern only intervenes on red. The lineage details
+are in [The gate/respawn lineage](#the-gaterespawn-lineage) below.
+
+### `map-reduce`
+
+A map-reduce run is submitted with a **splitter** item that carries a
+`MapReduceConfig` on its reserved `inputs.mapReduce` key:
+
+```ts
+interface MapReduceConfig {
+  map:    SpawnTemplate & { needsKey?: string; outputPath?: string };
+  reduce: SpawnTemplate & { keyPrefix?: string };
+}
+```
+
+`plan` validates the config (and rejects runs with more than one splitter);
+the actual fan-out happens in `onTaskDone`, in two phases:
+
+1. **Phase 1 ā€” splitter done.** When the cause item is the splitter itself,
+   the pattern reads `splitter.outputRefs` directly off the in-memory
+   `ItemState` (already populated by the engine), sorts the keys for
+   replay determinism, and emits one item per key with `id: map-${k}`.
+   Each map item runs the configured map executor and binds the splitter's
+   output for that key into `needs[needsKey ?? 'input']`. The directive's
+   `depends_on` is empty; the engine's normalize step auto-unions
+   `needs[*].from` into `depends_on`, so the map item ends up depending
+   on the splitter.
+2. **Phase 2 ā€” every map done.** When the cause is a `map-${k}` and every
+   `map-${k}` is `done` and no `reduce` item exists yet, the pattern emits
+   a single item with `id: reduce` that runs the configured reduce
+   executor and binds each map's output into
+   `needs[${keyPrefix ?? 'part'}-${k}]`.
+
+The fan-out width is unknown at submit time ā€” that is the whole point. You
+submit a run with just the splitter, and the pattern grows it to N+1 items
+once the splitter has produced N output keys. There is no manifest-fetch
+step: the engine already attaches the splitter's `outputRefs` on the
+in-memory state, and the pattern reads it directly.
+
+## Queue-level pattern config
+
+Patterns are attached to queues, not to individual runs. A run submitted to a
+pattern-bound queue automatically participates in its pattern's phase; there
+is no per-run opt-in. The queue config is just `{ concurrency, pattern? }` ā€”
+the pattern field is the imported strategy object:
+
+```ts
+queues: {
+  'pipeline-q': { concurrency: 2, pattern: pipeline },
+  'fanout-q':   { concurrency: 8, pattern: mapReduce },
+  'default':    { concurrency: 4 },                    // no pattern ā†’ static
+},
+```
+
+A queue with no `pattern` key has no pattern phase at all ā€”
+`applyPatternPhase` short-circuits when the queue's pattern entry is
+`undefined`, which is behaviorally identical to configuring `staticDag`
+(whose hooks are both no-ops). The `concurrency` budget and `resourceLocks`
+semantics are unchanged regardless of pattern ā€” the pattern phase only
+decides *which items exist*; the engine decides *which of those items run
+at once*.
+
+Because pipelines and map-reduce read their per-item knobs off reserved
+input keys (`inputs.gate`, `inputs.mapReduce`), the queue config itself
+stays tiny. The gate/respawn policy of a pipeline gate, and the map/reduce
+templates of a fan-out run, ride on the items the caller submits.
+
+The pattern phase runs **after** the engine tick and **before** the seal
+check. A run that was just extended structurally cannot seal on that same
+tick, because the newly spawned items enter as `pending` and are therefore
+not terminal. The seal check sees live items and correctly defers.
+
+## `extendRun` and `run.extended` audit entries
+
+The pattern phase never writes items directly into the run-state store. All
+spawns flow through the audited **`extendRun`** seam:
+
+1. A pattern's `onTaskDone` returns a `SpawnDirective` ā€” new `WorkItem`
+   descriptors with deterministic ids and their `depends_on` edges (in the
+   run's pre-namespace id space).
+2. `extendRun` first filters out items whose namespaced id already exists in
+   the store (the id-skip step that makes the call idempotent on replay),
+   then normalizes the remainder and validates the *merged* graph through
+   the same `validateRun` called at submit time. An invalid fragment
+   (unknown executor, dangling `depends_on`, runaway-fuse overrun) makes
+   `extendRun` throw; `applyPatternPhase` catches the throw, logs it to
+   stderr, and continues with the next directive ā€” the run carries on
+   without the bad spawn.
+3. On success, every new item is written to the run-state store and
+   attributed to the actor `pattern:<queueName>` rather than to the
+   original submitter.
+4. An audit entry of **kind** `run.extended` is appended, naming the run
+   id, the cause item (the terminal item whose completion triggered this
+   spawn), the actor, and a timestamp.
+
+```
+{ kind: "run.extended",
+  runId: "r-abc123",
+  itemId: "gate-test",
+  actor: "pattern:pipeline-q",
+  at: "2026-06-04T09:12:03.441Z" }
+```
+
+The queue name is encoded only implicitly through the actor string. There
+is no `pattern`, `queue`, or `spawnedIds` field on the entry ā€” the spawned
+ids are recoverable by diffing the run graph against the previous audit
+snapshot.
+
+Spawn ids are deterministic by construction, but the exact format is
+pattern-specific. Pipeline respawn uses `${base}-fix-${attempt}` for the
+fix item and `${base}~${next}` for the gate copy and any skipped-descendant
+copies. Map-reduce uses `map-${outputKey}` and `reduce`. After `extendRun`
+accepts them, the store further namespaces every id as
+`${runId}\x1f${id}` (U+001F UNIT SEPARATOR) so two runs with identically
+named items never collide. Because spawn ids are deterministic, a
+crash-and-rescan re-derives the same directive; `extendRun`'s id-skip
+absorbs it (returning the empty list), no items are appended, and no new
+`run.extended` entry is written. Idempotency requires no extra dedup
+table.
+
+The `run.extended` entry is the point in the audit trail where the dynamic
+growth becomes attributable and verifiable. `agora verify` reads it to
+reconstruct the provenance graph covering both the original items and all
+spawned items ā€” no separate verification path for dynamic runs.
+
+## The gate/respawn lineage
+
+A pipeline gate is an ordinary work item whose `inputs.gate` carries a
+`GateConfig`. The gate's pass/fail signal comes from the engine's per-item
+verify outcome on the gate's `ItemState`, not from any specific output file
+convention: the pattern treats the gate as **red** when
+
+```ts
+item.status === 'failed' ||
+(item.status === 'done' && item.verify?.passed === false)
+```
+
+and as **green** otherwise. There is no `outputs/gate.json` convention in
+the pattern layer.
+
+**Pass path.** Gate `done` with `verify.passed !== false`: `onTaskDone`
+returns `null` and the engine's ordinary dep-resolver moves on, because
+the next pre-declared item already has `depends_on` pointing at the gate
+(either because the caller wrote it that way or because `pipeline.plan`
+injected it). The pattern adds nothing.
+
+**Fail path (respawn).** Gate red and `gate.onRed === 'spawn-fix'`:
+`respawnLineage` runs. It returns the empty list ā€” and therefore the
+pattern emits nothing ā€” when the gate's attempt number is already past
+`maxFixAttempts` (default `1`), when any lineage member is `cancelled`,
+or when no `fixTemplate` was configured. If all guards pass, it builds:
+
+- a **fix item** with id `${base}-fix-${attempt}` whose `needs.work` binds
+  the gate's `subject` item's patch product; if the gate was done-but-red
+  and carries a `findings` output ref, that binds into `needs.findings`;
+  if the gate `failed`, the gate's `reason` is folded into the fix's
+  `inputs.gateReason` as plain data (a failed gate has no `outputRefs`,
+  so provenance closure cannot bind to it);
+- a **gate copy** with id `${base}~${next}` carrying the original gate's
+  static `WorkItem` fields, but with every edge remapped through a
+  substitution map `S` so that the copy now depends on the fix item
+  instead of the original subject;
+- a **copy of every skipped descendant** of the failed gate, with id
+  `${parseAttempt(d).base}~${next}`, edges similarly remapped through
+  `S`.
+
+The lineage = the gate plus every item transitively reachable from it via
+`depends_on` whose status is `skipped` (the items the engine cascaded
+after the gate failed). `respawnLineage` returns these new `WorkItem`s;
+the pattern wraps them in a `SpawnDirective`; `extendRun` appends them;
+the engine schedules them on the next tick.
+
+**Respawn exhaustion.** Once the gate's attempt count exceeds
+`maxFixAttempts`, `respawnLineage` returns the empty list, `onTaskDone`
+returns `null`, the pattern emits nothing, and the run settles with the
+failed gate intact. Downstream items remain `skipped` from the engine's
+ordinary cascade phase; nothing in the pattern logic special-cases this.
+
+The lineage is an **append**, not a loop. The failed branch is preserved
+as permanent nodes in the graph. Auditors can read the full history:
+first attempt, gate failure, fix item, gate copy, second-attempt outcome.
+No state is overwritten.
+
+## The forward-arc-never-rewind invariant
+
+Every item in every agora run graph obeys one structural rule:
+
+> **A `depends_on` edge may only point at an item whose id was present in
+> the run graph at the time the dependent item was created.**
+
+This means every edge points *backward* in time. The graph is always a
+DAG. Patterns are the only mechanism that adds items after submit, and
+`extendRun` enforces the rule by running the merged graph through
+`validateRun`: any `depends_on` reference in a spawn directive that names
+an item id not yet in the run is rejected as an unknown dependency.
+
+Why does this matter?
+
+- **The engine's dep-resolver is acyclic by assumption.** It iterates
+  over items and checks `depends_on` against a terminal-status map. A
+  cycle would cause the resolver to spin forever. The invariant makes a
+  cycle structurally impossible.
+- **Replay is deterministic.** Because no item can depend on something
+  that doesn't exist yet, replaying the audit log in order always
+  produces a valid state: each `run.extended` entry's `depends_on`
+  references are already present from earlier entries or the original
+  submit.
+- **Provenance closure is total.** `agora verify` walks `depends_on`
+  backward from every terminal item to the inputs. A forward arc would
+  create a reference to a not-yet-existing node ā€” a gap in the closure.
+  The invariant means verify's walk always terminates at known inputs.
+- **Lineages are safe.** A pipeline respawn *feels* like going backward,
+  but the lineage items are new nodes appended after the failed gate.
+  They depend on items already in the graph (backward arcs); nothing in
+  the old branch depends on them (which would be a forward arc into the
+  future). The circle is semantic, not structural.
+
+The invariant is checked mechanically in `validateRun` and re-checked in
+`extendRun` on every spawn. There is no runtime mode that relaxes it.
